<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,789,1537]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,862,888]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bidzilya" authorityYear="2008" box="[324,536,862,888]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Metanarsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amseli">
<emphasis box="[324,536,862,888]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Metanarsia amseli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from two females collected in South 
<collectingCountry box="[1143,1188,863,889]" name="Iran" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Iran</collectingCountry>
(Bidzilya 2008). The males from 
<collectingCountry box="[290,352,898,924]" name="Israel" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Israel</collectingCountry>
are identical externally to 
<typeStatus box="[664,723,899,925]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">types</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bidzilya" authorityYear="2008" box="[766,878,898,924]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Metanarsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amseli">
<emphasis box="[766,878,898,924]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">M. amseli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the black pattern is more distinct (
<figureCitation box="[1337,1424,898,924]" captionStart="FIGS 27–29" captionStartId="21.[151,210,864,889]" captionTargetBox="[152,1431,186,829]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[152,1435,181,839]" captionText="FIGS 27–29. Chrysoesthia amseli Bidz. 27. Holotype, ♀. 28.Adult, ♂ (gen. slide 115/18, O. Bidzilya). 29. Male genitalia (gen. slide 115/18, O. Bidzilya)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468882" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468882/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). Bidzilya (2005) considered that 
<taxonomicName authority="Staudinger, 1871" authorityName="Staudinger" authorityYear="1871" box="[511,836,934,960]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Metanarsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[511,640,935,960]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Metanarsia</emphasis>
Staudinger, 1871
</taxonomicName>
can be separated from 
<taxonomicName authority="Hubner, 1825" authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1825" box="[1095,1402,933,960]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Chrysoesthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1095,1243,934,960]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Chrysoesthia</emphasis>
Hübner, 1825
</taxonomicName>
by the absence of the signum in the corpus bursae of the female genitalia. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Karsholt, O. &amp; Vives Moreno, A." box="[1063,1436,970,997]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="649 - 653" refId="ref57640" refString="Karsholt, O. &amp; Vives Moreno, A. (2014) Two new Gelechiidae for the Iberian Peninsula (Lepidoptera: Gelechiidae). SHILAP Revista de Lepidopterologia, 42 (168), 649 - 653." type="journal article" year="2014">Karsholt &amp; Vives Moreno (2014)</bibRefCitation>
noted that the absence of pecten on antennal scape and short labial palpus in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1825" box="[1024,1172,1006,1032]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Chrysoesthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1024,1172,1006,1032]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Chrysoesthia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are more reliable characters for separating this genus from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Staudinger" authorityYear="1871" box="[569,698,1043,1068]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Metanarsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[569,698,1043,1068]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Metanarsia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Based on this suggestion we transfer 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bidzilya" authorityYear="2008" box="[1132,1242,1042,1068]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Metanarsia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amseli">
<emphasis box="[1132,1242,1042,1068]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">M. amseli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to 
<emphasis box="[1279,1436,1042,1068]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hubner" authorityYear="1825" box="[1279,1430,1042,1068]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Chrysoesthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Chrysoesthia</taxonomicName>
:
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Bidzilya, 2008)" authorityName="Bidzilya &amp; Karsholt &amp; Kravchenko &amp; Šumpich" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="Bidzilya" baseAuthorityYear="2008" box="[151,566,1078,1104]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Chrysoesthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amseli" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,378,1078,1104]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Chrysoesthia amseli</emphasis>
(Bidzilya, 2008)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[572,699,1078,1104]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[572,699,1078,1104]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
Below we provide the first description of the male genitalia of this species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,789,1537]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,371,1149,1176]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[387,473,1150,1176]" captionStart="FIGS 27–29" captionStartId="21.[151,210,864,889]" captionTargetBox="[152,1431,186,829]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[152,1435,181,839]" captionText="FIGS 27–29. Chrysoesthia amseli Bidz. 27. Holotype, ♀. 28.Adult, ♂ (gen. slide 115/18, O. Bidzilya). 29. Male genitalia (gen. slide 115/18, O. Bidzilya)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3468882" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3468882/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
). Uncus rounded; gnathos narrow, elongated, membranous, with rounded apex; tegumen trapezoidal, anterior margin straight; valva broad at base, distal portion straight, apex weakly broadened, rounded, extending to about half length of uncus; basal part of sacculus broad, sub-rectangular, inner margin with two or three denticles, posteromedial corner rounded, distal half narrow, digitate, straight, extending to ¾ length of valva; saccus stout, broad at base, then narrowed towards truncate apex; phallus as long as valva, weakly constricted in middle, distal ¾ narrowed, apex weakly pointed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,789,1537]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1366,1392]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Remarks.</emphasis>
The male genitalia are most similar to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Karsholt &amp; Vives, 2014" authorityName="Karsholt &amp; Vives" authorityYear="2014" box="[860,1293,1366,1392]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Chrysoesthia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hispanica">
<emphasis box="[860,1017,1366,1392]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Ch. hispanica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Karsholt, O. &amp; Vives Moreno, A." box="[1024,1293,1366,1392]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" pagination="649 - 653" refId="ref57640" refString="Karsholt, O. &amp; Vives Moreno, A. (2014) Two new Gelechiidae for the Iberian Peninsula (Lepidoptera: Gelechiidae). SHILAP Revista de Lepidopterologia, 42 (168), 649 - 653." type="journal article" year="2014">Karsholt &amp; Vives, 2014</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
but differ in sub-triangular rather than horseshoe shaped saccus and apically less narrowed phallus. The two species are externally different.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1297,1473,1501]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,789,1537]" box="[199,1297,1473,1501]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1473,1500]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Biology.</emphasis>
Host plant unknown. Adults have been collected in April in 
<collectingCountry box="[973,1018,1475,1501]" name="Iran" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Iran</collectingCountry>
and in October in 
<collectingCountry box="[1227,1293,1474,1500]" name="Israel" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Israel</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
